---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '@/lib/withBase';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import ConstellationCrossAuth from '@/components/react/ConstellationCrossAuth.tsx';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Cross-authentication"
  description="How a changing subset of Galileo satellites authenticates the whole constellation via self- and cross-authentication."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="2 · OSNMA on the signal"
    title="A moving constellation, cross-authenticated"
    lead="Not every satellite transmits OSNMA, and the ones that do keep changing. Yet the whole constellation stays authenticated — thanks to self- and cross-authentication."
  />

  <p>
    OSNMA is broadcast by a <strong>subset</strong> of the Galileo satellites, and
    that subset is dynamic: a receiver cannot assume any particular satellite will
    be carrying OSNMA at any moment. Because the TESLA chain and the DSMs are common
    to the constellation, this is fine — but it raises a question: how do satellites
    that are <em>not</em> transmitting OSNMA get authenticated?
  </p>

  <h2>Self vs cross authentication</h2>
  <p>
    The answer is in two fields of every tag: <strong>PRN_A</strong>, the satellite
    transmitting the tag, and <strong>PRN_D</strong>, the satellite whose data the
    tag authenticates <DocRef doc="icd" section="4.2.1" />.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Self-authentication</strong> — when <Formula tex="\text{PRN}_A = \text{PRN}_D" />,
      a satellite authenticates its own navigation data. Tag0 in every MACK is a
      self-authentication tag.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cross-authentication</strong> — when <Formula tex="\text{PRN}_A \neq \text{PRN}_D" />,
      a transmitting satellite authenticates <em>another</em> satellite's data, even
      if that other satellite carries no OSNMA at all.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>Step through a few epochs and watch the transmitting set change while coverage stays complete:</p>

  <ConstellationCrossAuth client:visible />

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      Cross-authentication is what makes a partial, shifting OSNMA deployment work.
      A handful of transmitting satellites can vouch for the data of many more, so a
      receiver authenticates every satellite it uses for a fix — not only the ones
      currently sending OSNMA.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      The fixed sequence of which tag slots are self- vs cross-authentication, and
      for which satellites, is governed by the
      <a href={withBase('/structures/maclt')}>MAC look-up table</a>. The "S" and "E" markers in
      those sequences are exactly self- and cross-authentication.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
